'''Riboga''' the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]] was a former [[Crime lord/Legends|crime lord]] of the [[Cularin system/Legends|Cularin system]]. Referred to as the "Exalted Disgusting One" at least twice, the first time he heard it, he found it funny; the second time he heard it, he demanded a tribute, or simply the "Exalted Riboga the Hutt," Riboga controlled crime in the [[Cularin/Legends|Cularin]] system from [[110 BBY]] to [[53 BBY/Legends|53 BBY]], and then since the [[Clone Wars/Legends|Clone Wars]] onwards.

==Biography==
Riboga came to [[Cularin system/Legends|Cularin system]] as an exile, but he soon managed to pull the [[Smugglers' Confederation]] under his control in [[110 BBY]], and established a successful criminal [[Organization]], focused mostly on smuggling, gambling, loansharking and, from [[78 BBY]] to his retirement, [[Slavery/Legends|slaving]].<ref name="LFC">''[[Living Force Campaign Guide]]''</ref>

Riboga loaned many of the [[Smuggler/Legends|smugglers]] money to upgrade their [[Starship/Legends|ships]], particularly the more recalcitrant ones. As an alternative to paying back the exorbitant interest rates, the smugglers could enter periods of exclusive service to the [[Hutt/Legends|Hutt]], essentially becoming his indentured servants. In this way, Riboga further brought the smugglers under his control. [[Gungan/Legends|Gungan]] [[Ace/Legends|ace]] [[Starfighter/Legends|starfighter]] [[Pilot/Legends|pilot]] [[Piknab Carsels]], while not exactly a smuggler, became one of Riboga's pilots in [[Varna Biqua]] this way.<ref name="LFC" />

When Riboga decided to live part-time in the [[City/Legends|city]] of [[Tolea Biqua]] on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] [[Genarius]], a city he had commissioned, he also decided to organize the local political power groups in a similar way. Appealing to the greed of the [[Governor/Legends|governors]] of the most powerful cities, but officially to facilitate control of Genarius, Riboga organized a [[Central Council (Genarius)|Central Council]] to deal with planetary affairs, including new trading deals with extra-planetary interests and a protection tax for the less important cities. The Council was composed of two representatives from each of Genarius's five largest cities, including Tolea Biqua. In its early years, Riboga sat as head of the Council himself to hold a tight control on it, but once he was satisfied with the representatives, he started letting them choose their own leader.<ref name="LFC" />

While Riboga could never annihilate the independent [[Pirate/Legends|pirates]]<ref name="UW">{{LivingForce|Between the Worlds: UnderWorld}}</ref> in the [[Cularin asteroid belt|asteroid belt]], he learned a lot from them. 17 years after arriving, he ordered the building of a secret [[Asteroid/Legends|asteroid]] headquarters for use in criminal operations; the base took [[91 BBY|2 years]] to build, and was practical and full of Hutt opulence. Then, he ordered the creation of a [[Nirama's public asteroid|second asteroid base]] to meet with his smugglers, [[Trade Federation/Legends|Trade Federation]] representatives, and other associates. He also built a mansion in [[Mikish]] on [[Cularin/Legends|Cularin]], and an office in Tolea Biqua on Genarius. He did own a [[Sail barge/Legends|floating barge]], where he sent an appointed waiter, [[Bez]], to repeatedly duel against creatures from across [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy]].<ref name="LFC" /> He was also once the owner of a number of [[L8O protocol droid|L80-series protocol droids]], such as [[L8O-RC|L80-RC]].

One of Riboga's business associates was zoo proprietor [[Hlisk Squin]], based in the city of [[Bollin]] on Cularin. Squin also smuggled slaves for the Hutt using animal containers. Other partners included the [[Bothan/Legends|Bothan]] [[Information broker/Legends|information broker]] [[Tchaw Fenn]], who lived in [[Friz Harammel]] on [[Genarius]], and the [[Twi'lek/Legends|Twi'lek]] [[Assassin/Legends|assassin]] and masseuse [[Lalo]]. Lalo worked for one of Riboga's lieutenants, but when Riboga killed her boss she became a freelancer.<ref name="LFC" />

Being an important figure on Genarius, Riboga was the person to contact when [[Verga Mer Mining Company]] tried to expand their interest to Genarius. Verga Mer tried to deal with the less powerful cities themselves, and while Riboga had not felt personally insulted, he later ignored all the five audience petitions from Verga Mer.<ref name="LFC" />

Riboga fronted money and supplies, including [[Droid/Legends|droid]] workers such as [[4-KT]], to the independent droid [[QS-2D]] to begin its mining operations on [[Uffel]] around [[90 BBY/Legends|90 BBY]]. QS-2D tried its best to convince Riboga that it was acting as a proxy for his [[Twi'lek/Legends|Twi'lek]] masters, but the masters had died when reaching Uffel and QS-2D had intended to become the master of a droid factory in non-breathable Uffel.<ref name="LFC" />

In [[78 BBY]], Riboga decided to expand his business and include slavery, which became his main and more profitable business. Due to the relative isolation of Cularin system, Riboga could use the system as a stop point to transport slaves from the [[Core Worlds/Legends|Core Worlds]] to the [[Outer Rim Territories/Legends|Outer Rim]], although he always replaced the transporting smuggler in Cularin. Riboga, in a lesser measure, also kidnapped some local [[Tarasin]]s to use them as slaves.<ref name="LFC" />

In [[72 BBY/Legends|72 BBY]], Riboga began sponsoring starship races through the [[Space worm/Legends|space worm]]-dug tunnels of [[Eskaron]], a moon of Genarius. This practice would continue for at least forty years. Riboga backed [[Z-95 Headhunter/Legends|Z-95]] pilot [[Likk Nibk]] in the races, with threats on Nibk's life as a motivation.<ref name="LFC" />

At some point, Riboga placed a conditional [[Bounty/Legends|bounty]] on the head of smuggler [[Nadin Paal]]: It was only to be active should Paal ever leave the Cularin system. The [[Bounty Hunters' Guild/Legends|Bounty Hunters' Guild]] decided to keep an eye on Paal and wait for him to make a wrong move.<ref name="LFC" />

Eventually rising costs, principally arising from the struggles between his smugglers and the various independent pirate groups of Cularin, plus the high cost of space travel in that particular system, caused him to question the worthwhileness of continuing his operations. His [[Majordomo/Legends|majordomo]], a strange being named [[Nirama]], heard Riboga talking about this. In actuality, Nirama had been skimming money, diverting profits, and altering the books to make Riboga's business dealings seem less profitable due to "additional expenses" for the isolation of Cularin. Although Riboga questioned and even executed some of his minions, he could not track the problem to Nirama.<ref name="LFC" />

In [[53 BBY/Legends|53 BBY]], Nirama made a wager at their regular [[Sabacc/Legends|sabacc]] game of a quarter-million [[Galactic Credit Standard/Legends|credits]] against Riboga's Cularin operations, and won. Riboga took the loss well, laughing and returning to [[Nal Hutta/Legends|Nal Hutta]] with only his money and some of his more loyal minions.<ref name="LFC" />

When Riboga left the system, he sold many of his possessions. Nirama got Riboga's mansion in Mikish, his office on Genarius, and both of his asteroid bases. Riboga's interests in Uffel were bought out by QS-2D. The local black market suddenly had a great supply of [[Thermal detonator/Legends|thermal detonators]] and [[Blaster cannon/Legends|heavy blaster cannons]]. Riboga's servant droids, such as [[Interrogation droid/Legends|torture droid]] [[IT-O9]], were also sold to new owners who were unaware of any customization Riboga had ordered on the machines. He sold his barge to a pair of Hutt-hating [[Trandoshan/Legends|Trandoshans]] that converted it into a [[Casino/Legends|casino]] creatively named [[Riboga's Barge]], where they mocked the Hutt's customs and criticized Riboga's virility, as had not had any children at that point.<ref name="LFC" />

Riboga had a lasting affect on the Cularin system beyond organizing its crime. After Riboga's departure, the Central Council of Genarius started to become the legitimate governing body it had always appeared to be, though they remained focused on their own interests.

At some point, Riboga gave [[Velin Wir]], leader of the [[Metatheran Cartel]] in the Cularin system in [[31 BBY/Legends|31 BBY]], a unique gift&mdash;a [[Lightsaber/Legends|lightsaber]] which was proximity linked to a tiny [[Thermal detonator/Legends|thermal detonator]] implanted in Wir's chest. The exact nature of their business arrangement remained unknown.<ref name="ARv">{{LivingForce|Eye of the Sun: Revelation and Refutation}}</ref> Around [[32 BBY/Legends|32 BBY]], Riboga gave a juvenile [[Rancor/Legends|rancor]] named [[Bender (rancor)|Bender]] to Nirama as a [[naming day]] gift, seeming to bear no malice for having lost their bet.<ref name="TW">{{LivingForce|Between the Worlds: TopWorld}}</ref> Certain smugglers such as [[Vel Pastar]], who had worked under Riboga since his takeover in 110 BBY, remained in Cularin and worked under Nirama, even if they disliked his different approach to business.<ref name="TW" /> Other employees, like the cook [[Karlo]], learned to avoid political issues under Riboga's regime and chose not to defy authority, whatever form it took.<ref name="MW">{{LivingForce|Between the Worlds: MidWorld}}</ref>

